Ah, I see the issue! Looking at the flag parsing code:

```typescript
if (args[i] === "--resume" || args[i] === "-r") {
    resumeSession = args[i + 1] || "latest";
    i++;
}
```

When you run `bun run agent.ts -r` without a session ID argument, it does `args[i + 1]` which is `undefined`, so it falls back to `"latest"` — that part is fine.

But the issue is `bun run` — the `run` might be consuming flags. Try:

```bash
bun agent.ts -r
```

Or if that's not the issue, let me check what's actually happening:

Oh! So it worked fine — it just printed "No previous sessions found." as a warning, then created a new session and kept going. That's the expected behavior for a first run with `-r`.

The flow in the code is:

```typescript
if (resumeSession === "latest") {
    const latestId = getLatestSessionId();
    if (!latestId) {
      console.error("No previous sessions found."); // ← you saw this
      sessionId = generateSessionId();               // ← then it made a new one
    }
    ...
}
```

So it gracefully fell back to creating a fresh session. Nothing broken — you were just telling me the full startup story! 😄

